electric dipole polarizing the surrounding region. By symmetry, the defect level energy and the electric polarization of an isolated defect in bulk $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3}$ do not depend on the orientation of its dipole moment.

This behavior changes in a FTJ (Figs. 1(c) and 1(e)), where the energetics and electronic properties of the antisite defect depend of the defect position in the $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3}$ layer. We find that the $\mathrm{Ti}_{\mathrm{Sr}}$ defect located at the interface has $0.11 \mathrm{eV}$ lower energy than that placed in the middle of the junction. Due to the depolarizing field associated with the interface, $\mathrm{Ti}_{\mathrm{Sr}}$ offcentering is larger for polarization pointing to the interface $\left(\mathrm{P}_{\rightarrow}\right.$ state) than for polarization pointing towards the center of the junction $\left(\mathrm{P}_{\leftarrow}\right.$ state). Specifically, for $\mathrm{Ti}_{\text {Sr }}$ placed in the second layer from the interface (Figs. 1(c) and 1(e)) the offcentering is $0.78 \AA$ for the $\mathrm{P}_{\rightarrow}$ state and $0.72 \AA$ for the $\mathrm{P}_{\leftarrow}$ state. This difference is reduced as the defect is placed closer to the central layer.

These results indicate that in experimental conditions the defect distribution will be inhomogeneous with the preference of defects to be located closer to the interface. In addition, for FTJs with different metal electrodes or different interface terminations, there will be certain asymmetry in the energy and polarization state of the defect level due to the intrinsic electric field across the FTJ. To qualitatively reflect this asymmetry, we analyze the electronic and transport properties of the $\mathrm{Pt} / \mathrm{SrTiO}_{3} / \mathrm{Pt} \mathrm{FTJ}$ with a single $\mathrm{Ti}_{\mathrm{Sr}}$ defect placed in the second layer from the interface as shown in Figs. 1(c) and 1(e).

Figures 1(d) and 1(f) show the local density of states (LDOS) across the $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3}$ layer for right $\mathrm{P}_{\rightarrow}$ (Fig. 1(c)) and left $\mathrm{P}_{\leftarrow}$ (Fig. 1(e)) polarization states, respectively. It is seen that the LDOS projected onto the layer with the $\mathrm{Ti}_{\text {Sr }}$ defect exhibits a localized state in the energy gap of $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3}$ similar to that for bulk $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3}$ (Fig. 1(b)). The energy position of this state depends on polarization orientation: for the $\mathrm{P}_{\leftarrow}$ polarization state the defect level appears deeper in energy (Fig. 1(f)) as compared to the $\mathrm{P}_{\rightarrow}$ polarization state where the defect level moves closer to the Fermi energy (Fig. 1(d)) . This behavior is explained by the asymmetric position of the defect in the FTJ and proximity to the metal electrode. The $\mathrm{Ti}_{S r}$ defect produces an electric dipole polarizing the surrounding region. The electrostatic potential energy associated with this dipole increases in the direction opposite to the dipole orientation. Due to the proximity of the Pt electrode where the electric field is screened, the potential energy increases (decreases) when moving away from the interface into $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3}$ for the $\mathrm{P}_{\rightarrow}\left(\mathrm{P}_{\leftarrow}\right)$ state. This behavior is seen from the variation in the conduction band minimum (CBM) and the valence band maximum (VBM) depending on polarization direction (orange lines in Figs. 1(d) and 1(f)). The increase (decrease) in the potential energy with respect to that in $\mathrm{Pt}$ pushes the defect level up (down) in energy for the $\mathrm{P}_{\rightarrow}\left(\mathrm{P}_{\leftarrow}\right)$ state. We find that the shift in the defect level energy with polarization reversal is $0.16 \mathrm{eV}$ when it is located in the second layer from the $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3} / \mathrm{Pt}$ interface. This value increases up to $0.26 \mathrm{eV}$ for the defect placed in the first layer and drops down to $0.06 \mathrm{eV}$ for the defect in the third layer.

The polarization-controlled localized states in the band gap of $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3}$ affect tunneling conductance. Fig. 2(a) shows the calculated total transmission $T=T_{\uparrow}+T_{\downarrow}$ across the $\mathrm{Pt} / \mathrm{SrTiO}_{3} / \mathrm{Pt}$ FTJ as a function of energy $E$. The overall trend for the transmission being enhanced for energies approaching the CBM and VBM and reduced for midgap energies is consistent with the energy-dependent decay rate of the evanescent states in $\mathrm{SrTiO}_{3}$ (see, e.g., ref. [12]). On top of this trend, however, there is a dramatic variation in the transmission probability for energies crossing the $\mathrm{Ti}_{\mathrm{Sr}}$ defect levels indicated in Fig. 2(a) by the background LDOS. The observed variation is correlated with the polarization dependent LDOS, revealing tendency for $T(E)$ to be enhanced in regions where LDOS is high and resulting in crossover between $\mathrm{P}_{\rightarrow}$ and $\mathrm{P}_{\leftarrow}$ dominated transmission depending on energy.

This correlation becomes especially evident when we consider the spin polarization of transmission defined by ratio $\left(T_{\uparrow}-T_{\downarrow}\right) /\left(T_{\uparrow}+T_{\downarrow}\right)$. Since the localized defect states appear\\
